Actually, that analogy would be applicable if a smallish guild had gotten a flag kill by getting assistance from BoTS, wouldn't it ?<br>
<br>
<blockquote style="padding-left:0.5em; margin-left:0; margin-right:0; margin-top:0; margin-bottom:0; border-left:solid 2">At how many “individuals” does it become a valid group view? I see Tindi, SotE, LoM, NB, BotS, VoF, all saying that teaming is against the spirit of the rotation system. And I see one or two guilds of similar “status” (again, lack of a better word, but what a L 20-30 guild thinks of how PoP is handled is irrelevant imo) saying that teaming, while not something to be proud of, is not a bad thing either. I also disagree with your premise that any subjective or objective basis for “what is deserved” is about any one individual’s arbitrary views.</blockquote><br>
<br>
Even assuming your observations are correct on all of those guilds, there is an implication here, I think, that anytime a majority of guilds (or just people ?) think something is good, RTA will jump into action and enforce it.  Is this the function of the RTA, to enforce group views ?  I don't think the fact that a large group people have determined what they would be 'proud of' should necessarily have anything to do with RTA.  If this IS the function of the RTA (or 'in the spirit of'), than my apologies for misunderstanding the scope of the RTA.<br>
<br>
<blockquote style="padding-left:0.5em; margin-left:0; margin-right:0; margin-top:0; margin-bottom:0; border-left:solid 2">The rule about not teaming on rotation mobs has been in place since BotS and KEG worked out the first rotation on Trak</blockquote><br>
<br>
This is another example of what I meant by two issues getting intertwined.  I am under the impression that RTA was set up to ensure that guilds have equal shots at raid level mobs, not as a moral reward system.  If you want to debate that any actions taken were abusive of the system, that's fine.  However, it seems like you are trying to apply the original intent of the system (to promote equal opportunity, as I understand it) to justify that an action lives up to your idea of 'pride' (or, as you say, the 'group view' of it).<br>
<br>
I can certainly see how teaming up on a rotation mob could be abused.  Theoretically, you could split a large guild into 5 small guilds, have them all assist each other and get on the rotation 5 times as often.  The question really should be "Is that, in EFFECT, what is happening here ?".<br>
<br>
I think a lot of the arguments fall through if you look at it only in the light of "Is it abusing the system and giving one or two guilds an advantage ?"<br>
